 of turtles", "work_id": 69123, "role": "director", "role_id": 938, "is_primary": true}, {"id": 2680489, "title": "Coral kingdom", "work_id": 66410, "role": "director", "role_id": 938, "is_primary": true}, {"id": 870569, "title": "Ocean oddities", "work_id": 86391, "role": "director", "role_id": 938, "is_primary": true}, {"id": 2103721, "title": "Australia's coral wonderland", "work_id": 88275, "role": "co-producer", "role_id": 915, "is_primary": true}, {"id": 2645580, "title": "Great Barrier Reef: marvels in miniature", "work_id": 70173, "role": "producer", "role_id": 1089, "is_primary": true}], "also_known_as": "", "date_of_birth": "01 JAN 1896", "date_of_death": "01 MAY 1969", "genders": [{"id": 9, "name": "Male", "slug": "male"}], "languages": [], "places_of_operation": [{"id": 3, "name": "Australia", "slug": "australia"}], "biography": "Noel Monkman (1896–1969) was an Australian filmmaker, born in New Zealand, best known for specialising in underwater photography. He was a press photographer in New Zealand before moving to Australia and jointing the Orpheum Theatre orchestra.\n\nHe established Australian Educational Films with F.W. Thring, directing a series of educational nature films about the Great Barrier Reef. He later made several documentaries as well as two dramatic feature films. He collaborated throughout his career with his wife Kitty.He and Kitty lived for a time on Green Island, acting as a volunteer air observer during World War II. Source: Wikidata; 01/08/2023", "biography_author": null, "date_of_biography": "2025-03-13T01:05:32.214001+11:00", "external_links": [{"id": 4789, "uri": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Noel_Monkman"}], "uuid": "c2eec576-a5b8-4649-9b70-6779db9569e4", "source": {"name": "Vernon", "slug": "vernon"}, "source_identifier": "4176", "external_references": [{"id": 26514, "source": {"name": "Wikidata", "slug": "wikidata"}, "source_identifier": "Q7047118"}, {"id": 30548, "source": {"name": "VIAF", "slug": "viaf"}, "source_identifier": "92211595"}, {"id": 30549, "source": {"name": "WorldCat", "slug": "worldcat"}, "source_identifier": "viaf-92211595"}], "date_modified": "2025-03-13T01:05:32.214281+11:00"}, {"id": 14078, "name": "Jacques-Yves Cousteau", "roles_in_work": [{"id": 2147783, "title": "Cries from the deep", "work_id": 85770, "role": "co-producer", "role_id": 915, "is_primary": true}, {"id": 2768602, "title": "Coral jungle", "work_id": 66409, "role": "producer", "role_id": 1089, "is_primary": true}, {"id": 1809433, "title": "Station 307", "work_id": 73174, "role": "producer", "role_id": 1089, "is_primary": true}, {"id": 2768616, "title": "Return of the sea elephant", "work_id": 75867, "role": "producer", "role_id": 1089, "is_primary": true}, {"id": 2749686, "title": "Green sea turtle", "work_id": 96925, "role": "production company", "role_id": 941, "is_primary": true}, {"id": 2713039, "title": "Epaves", "work_id": 67215, "role": "production company", "role_id": 941, "is_primary": true}], "also_known_as": "", "date_of_birth": "11 JUN 1910", "date_of_death": "25 JUN 1997", "genders": [{"id": 9, "name": "Male", "slug": "male"}], "languages": [{"id": 4, "name": "French", "slug": "french"}], "places_of_operation": [{"id": 17, "name": "France", "slug": "france"}], "biography": "Jacques-Yves Cousteau,  (, also UK: , French: [ʒak iv kusto]; 11 June 1910 – 25 June 1997) was a French naval officer,  oceanographer, filmmaker and author. He co-invented the first successful Aqua-Lung, open-circuit SCUBA (self-contained underwater breathing apparatus). The apparatus assisted him in producing some of the first underwater documentaries.\n\nCousteau wrote many books describing his undersea explorations. In his first book, The Silent World: A Story of Undersea Discovery and Adventure, Cousteau surmised the existence of the echolocation abilities of porpoises. The book was adapted into an underwater documentary called The Silent World. Co-directed by Cousteau and Louis Malle, it was one of the first films to use underwater cinematography to document the ocean depths in color. The film won the 1956 Palme d'Or at the Cannes Film Festival and remained the only documentary to do so until 2004, when Fahrenheit 9/11 received the award. It was also awarded the Academy Award for Best Documentary in 1957.\n\nFrom 1966 to 1976, he hosted The Undersea World of Jacques Cousteau, a documentary television series, presented on American commercial television stations. A second documentary series, The Cousteau Odyssey, ran from 1977 to 1982 on public television stations. Source: Wikidata; 15/08/2023", "biography_author": null, "date_of_biography": "2025-03-14T18:10:34.222366+11:00", "external_links": [{"id": 2343, "uri": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jacques_Cousteau"}], "uuid": "19624f10-f120-4be7-ba13-200e9b7af3d6", "source": {"name": "Vernon", "slug": "vernon"}, "source_identifier": "21168", "external_references": [{"id": 25238, "source": {"name": "Wikidata", "slug": "wikidata"}, "source_identifier": "Q83233"}, {"id": 29112, "source": {"name": "VIAF", "slug": "viaf"}, "source_identifier": "73851811"}, {"id": 29113, "source": {"name": "LOC Auth", "slug": "loc-auth"}, "source_identifier": "n81103293"}, {"id": 29114, "source": {"name": "WorldCat", "slug": "worldcat"}, "source_identifier": "lccn-n81103293"}], "date_modified": "2025-03-14T18:10:34.222651+11:00"}]}